        <p>Lipase (fat digestion), protease (protein digestion), and amylase (carbohydrate digestion) directly assist food breakdown, reducing the undigested substrate available for bacterial gas production. Effects within 30-60 minutes.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Probiotics: microbiome rebalancing</strong>
        <p>Clinically studied strains like L. acidophilus and B. lactis shift the gut microbiome toward lower gas-producing compositions. Requires 2-4 weeks of consistent use for meaningful bloating reduction.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Herbal carminatives: gas relief</strong>
        <p>Ginger, peppermint, and fennel relax intestinal smooth muscle, facilitating gas passage and reducing the trapped gas that causes distension and discomfort. Traditional use with some clinical support.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Prebiotic fiber: long-term gut health</strong>
        <p>Specific prebiotic fibers (partially hydrolyzed guar gum, acacia) selectively feed beneficial bacteria without producing the excess gas associated with rapidly fermentable fibers like inulin.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

